    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Performance Improvement of Cognitive Radio Networks Using Energy Efficient Spectrum Sensing Technique</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Kalimuthu.K</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Performance Improvement<br />Energy Efficient Spectrum Sensing Technique</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Nov-2013 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0136</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">With today’s increases in the usage of wireless applications and consequent
spectrum allocation, radio spectrum is becoming scarce. In practice, most of the
allotted spectrum is not used for long periods of time, due to the static frequency
allocation scheme. Cognitive radio is an emerging technology proposing the concept
of dynamic spectrum access as a solution to the problem of spectrum scarcity. Under
the proposed concept, non- licensed, secondary users can access the spectrum owned
by licensed primary users so long as interference to primary users is kept minimal.
Spectrum sensing is a crucial task in cognitive radio network whereby the
secondary users sense the spectrum to detect the presence or absence of any primary
user signal. In this research, an energy efficient spectrum sensing method is
proposed with a view to maximize the secondary user’s capacity by minimizing the
outage probability for Rayleigh fading channel. A also, the various performance of
the spectrum sensing like probability of detection, probability of false alarm and
sensing time are analyzed for a non-cooperative spectrum sensing method.
Several factors like fading and shadowing degrade the performance of
non-cooperative spectrum sensing. Cooperative spectrum sensing aims to improve
the detection sensitivity at low Signal to Noise Ratio (SNR) environments as well as
to fading channel where the primary users’ activities might be shadowed from the
local secondary user receiver by any existing intermediate obstacles. In this method,
increasing the number of secondary users will cause overload in the reporting
channel and due to continuous spectrum sensing, the lifetime of the cognitive radio network is reduced. Due to this, the overall system performance may be affected.
Cluster based cooperative scheme is addressed for this kind of scenario,. In this
research, for the cluster based cooperative scheme, energy efficient cluster head
selection is proposed, based on the received signal to noise ratio, without
considering the secondary users’ energy. Further, one more method is proposed for
selecting the cluster head, based on the considering secondary users’ energy using
fuzzy logic system. Simulation results show that, the proposed method is improved
the network performance and also prove that the lifetime of the secondary users
network is much longer than the existing LEACH-C based system.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/15145">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/15145</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
